<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98986457791673></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98986457791673><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98986457791673>RE: Wisdom or strenght</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98986457791673#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, May 14th 2:22 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Wisdom is the most important atribute for shaman, since it determins how much mana you get.&nbsp;&nbsp;At starting wisdom will give you a bit more mana than equipment wisdom.  However most of the time your total wisdom is not that important.  In groups how fast you regain mana is more important than how much mana you have.  After you get canablize shaman can regain mana faster than most other classes.  While soloing AC and the damage your weapon does are very important as well.  When I solo my wis is 149 (lvl 49) and I have yet to run out of mana on something I can kill.  <br><br>There are two times when total wisdom is important.  1 When learning skills like tailoring. 2. On a dragon raid When it is a one shot all or nothing fight.  <br><br>If you have been happy so far with your shaman I see no reason to start over.  <br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
